# ----------------------------------------------------------------------
# Units
# ----------------------------------------------------------------------

oakcurric:unit-3200
  a curric:Unit ;
  rdfs:label "Describe things and people: singular adjective agreement, to be being"@en ;
  curric:slug "describe-things-and-people-singular-adjective-agreement-to-be-being" ;
  rdfs:comment """In this unit, pupils use reference resources to write picture descriptions
  inspired by authentic poems, and story adaptations. They learn determiners ‘mi’ and ‘tu’,
  pronouns ‘él’ and ‘ella’ and ‘tener’ with meaning be in the contexts of age, states,
  friends, favourite things and Christmas."""@en ;
  curric:whyThisWhyNow """This unit develops pupils’ use of reference resources and builds on
  knowledge of nouns and adjectives, consolidated through written practice in new contexts.
  Having previously learnt the most common meaning of ‘tener’ to have, pupils now learn its
  idiomatic meaning to be. This, together with the learning of possessives ‘mi’ and ‘tu’ and
  pronouns ‘él’ and ‘la’ broadens pupils’ communicative range, enabling them to talk about age,
  physical states and their favourite things. Extending cultural knowledge, the end of this
  unit recycles new and previous language in the context of Christmas in Peru.""" ;
  curric:hasPriorKnowledgeRequirement
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3200-1 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3200-2 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3200-3 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3200-4 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3200-5 ;
  curric:id "3200"^^xsd:positiveInteger;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:29:23.348821Z"^^xsd:dateTime ;
  curric:isUnitOf
    natcurric:scheme-languages-key-stage-2 ;
  curric:includesThread
    oakcurric:thread-cultural-spotlight ,
    oakcurric:thread-ask-and-answer-spoken-questions ,
    oakcurric:thread-the-present ,
    oakcurric:thread-listen-and-respond-to-songs-and-rhymes ,
    oakcurric:thread-adjectives ,
    oakcurric:thread-verb-to-be-being .

oakcurric:unit-3498
  a curric:Unit ;
  rdfs:label "What I and others do: -AR and -ER singular verbs"@en ;
  curric:slug "what-i-and-others-do-ar-and-er-singular-verbs" ;
  rdfs:comment """In this unit, pupils use singular -er and -ar verbs, including stem-change verb
  ‘jugar’ to play, for end of school year activities, summer days and music lessons. They
  extend cultural knowledge learning names of several typical musical instruments from Peru.
  Pupils practise new sounds, v, b, and h."""@en ;
  curric:whyThisWhyNow """This unit expands pupils’ verb lexicon and their ability to manipulate
  verbs in the present tense, which are key learning for beginner language learners. Now that
  pupils already know several regular -ar and -er verbs, they learn a new verb ‘jugar’ to play,
  which includes a stem change. Bringing together knowledge of nouns, adjectives, -ar, -er and
  irregular verbs enables students to apply their learning to listen and respond to a more
  extended passage. Trickier sound-symbol correspondences v, b and h are introduced now that
  pupils are confident with easier sounds.""" ;
  curric:hasPriorKnowledgeRequirement
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3498-1 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3498-2 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3498-3 ;
  curric:id "3498"^^xsd:positiveInteger;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:29:23.374520Z"^^xsd:dateTime ;
  curric:isUnitOf
    natcurric:scheme-languages-key-stage-2 ;
  curric:includesThread
    oakcurric:thread-ask-and-answer-spoken-questions ,
    oakcurric:thread-the-present .

oakcurric:unit-3195
  a curric:Unit ;
  rdfs:label "What I and others have: 'tener' and singular nouns"@en ;
  curric:slug "what-i-and-others-have-tener-and-singular-nouns" ;
  rdfs:comment """In this unit, in the context of talking about belongings, pupils learn that nouns
  have grammatical gender and that this determines the word for a/an. They learn to use the
  first, second and third person forms of the verb ‘tener’ and that most adjectives come
  after the noun."""@en ;
  curric:whyThisWhyNow """The verbs ‘to have’ and ‘to be’ are the most frequent and essential early
  knowledge for pupils. The concept of grammatical gender is gateway knowledge to be able to
  use indefinite articles and nouns. New vocabulary is selected for its frequency and for the
  age-appropriate context of talking about personal belongings in class and at home. Revisited
  vocabulary and phonics ensure that pupils regularly encounter previously taught language to
  embed learning.""" ;
  curric:hasPriorKnowledgeRequirement
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3195-1 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3195-2 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3195-3 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3195-4 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3195-5 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3195-6 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3195-7 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3195-8 ;
  curric:id "3195"^^xsd:positiveInteger;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:29:23.456169Z"^^xsd:dateTime ;
  curric:isUnitOf
    natcurric:scheme-languages-key-stage-2 ;
  curric:includesThread
    oakcurric:thread-ask-and-answer-spoken-questions ,
    oakcurric:thread-nouns-and-determiners ,
    oakcurric:thread-verb-to-have-having ,
    oakcurric:thread-adjectives ,
    oakcurric:thread-questions .

oakcurric:unit-3508
  a curric:Unit ;
  rdfs:label "Cities and festivals: to go, to have, present tense"@en ;
  curric:slug "cities-and-festivals-to-go-to-have-present-tense" ;
  rdfs:comment """In this unit pupils use prior and new knowledge of nouns, adjectives, and
  irregular verbs in new and familiar contexts, ranging from the classroom and belongings to
  an exploration of three cities: Ovideo and Barcelona in Spain and Iquique in Chile.
  Phonics que, qui, r, rr, n, ñ, v, b are revisited."""@en ;
  curric:whyThisWhyNow """This unit anchors knowledge of previously taught high frequency irregular
  verbs before introducing singular forms of another irregular verb, ‘ir’ to go, going. Pupils
  develop their cultural knowledge of places where Spanish is spoken, learning about the
  Spanish cities of Oviedo and Barcelona and the Chilean city of Iquique. Appropriately, pupils
  also extend their knowledge of prepositions of destination and location and learn the compass
  points. This and other units connect multiple threads, including questions, negation, nouns
  and adjectives as pupils become more linguistically proficient.""" ;
  curric:hasPriorKnowledgeRequirement
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3508-1 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3508-2 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3508-3 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3508-4 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3508-5 ;
  curric:id "3508"^^xsd:positiveInteger;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:29:23.617627Z"^^xsd:dateTime ;
  curric:isUnitOf
    natcurric:scheme-languages-key-stage-2 ;
  curric:includesThread
    oakcurric:thread-the-present ,
    oakcurric:thread-questions ,
    oakcurric:thread-cultural-spotlight ,
    oakcurric:thread-verb-to-have-having .

oakcurric:unit-3509
  a curric:Unit ;
  rdfs:label "What I and others do: the verb 'hacer'"@en ;
  curric:slug "what-i-and-others-do-the-verb-hacer" ;
  rdfs:comment """In this unit, pupils use ‘hacer’ to understand short texts and ask and answer
  questions about birthdays and other celebrations. They learn to use ‘hacer’ meaning be
  with weather expressions and extend their sentences using the subordinating conjunction
  ‘cuando’, meaning when."""@en ;
  curric:whyThisWhyNow """Pupils will already know the singular forms of ‘hacer’ to do, make. This
  unit secures this knowledge in a new context, additionally connecting present tense use of
  ‘hacer’ with questions and negation, before introducing the idiomatic use of ‘hacer’ with
  weather expressions. Building on pupils’ use of simple and compound sentences, pupils learn
  to create longer sentences with subordinate clauses, using ‘cuando’. This unit’s cultural
  context explores the importance of the three Wise Men in Spain and students apply their
  knowledge in writing a letter to them.""" ;
  curric:hasPriorKnowledgeRequirement
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3509-1 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3509-2 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3509-3 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3509-4 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3509-5 ;
  curric:id "3509"^^xsd:positiveInteger;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:29:23.624805Z"^^xsd:dateTime ;
  curric:isUnitOf
    natcurric:scheme-languages-key-stage-2 ;
  curric:includesThread
    oakcurric:thread-the-present ,
    oakcurric:thread-negation ,
    oakcurric:thread-cultural-spotlight .

oakcurric:unit-3500
  a curric:Unit ;
  rdfs:label "Me and others: singular 'estar' (for states) and 'ser' (for traits)"@en ;
  curric:slug "me-and-others-singular-estar-for-states-and-ser-for-traits" ;
  rdfs:comment """This unit requires pupils to use ‘estar’ and ‘ser’ effectively to communicate
  about how they and others are today and what they are like in general. When using the new
  plural forms ‘estamos’ and ‘somos’, pupils need also to use plural adjective agreement,
  applied to familiar and new adjectives."""@en ;
  curric:whyThisWhyNow """This unit expands pupils’ knowledge of the gateway verbs ‘estar’ and
  ‘ser’, adding the first person plural forms ‘estamos’ and ‘somos’. Pupils practise the new
  plural forms ‘we are’ alongside the three singular forms. They learn regular plural adjective
  agreement to complement new plural verb knowledge. As previously, ‘estar’ for states is
  contrasted with ‘ser’ for traits. In a later unit, pupils will learn the third person plural
  forms ‘they are’. Familiar vowel sounds are secured in a new focus on consonant-vowel
  syllables, and high frequency known and new adjectives are practised.""" ;
  curric:hasPriorKnowledgeRequirement
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3500-1 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3500-2 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3500-3 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3500-4 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3500-5 ;
  curric:id "3500"^^xsd:positiveInteger;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:29:23.716646Z"^^xsd:dateTime ;
  curric:isUnitOf
    natcurric:scheme-languages-key-stage-2 ;
  curric:includesThread
    oakcurric:thread-adjectives ,
    oakcurric:thread-verb-to-be-being .

oakcurric:unit-3197
  a curric:Unit ;
  rdfs:label "How many: 'hay', numbers, plural nouns"@en ;
  curric:slug "how-many-hay-numbers-plural-nouns" ;
  rdfs:comment """In this unit pupils learn the numbers 1-12. They learn to add -s to form plural
  nouns for all nouns ending in a vowel. Pupils learn that the irregular verb form ‘hay’
  means ‘there is’ and ‘there are’ and combine this with noun knowledge to ask and answer
  about how many of each item there are."""@en ;
  curric:whyThisWhyNow """Pupils will already know how to use singular nouns with indefinite and
  definite articles. In this unit, pupils extend their knowledge of nouns, learning how to
  pluralise nouns that end in a vowel. Revisiting prior knowledge of ‘tener’ in statements and
  intonation questions, pupils use ‘tengo/tienes’ and ‘hay’ to ask and answer questions with
  numbers and familiar, high frequency plural nouns. Pupils will go on to extend their
  repertoire of determiners to plural ‘unos’ and ‘unas’, meaning some.""" ;
  curric:hasPriorKnowledgeRequirement
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3197-1 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3197-2 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3197-3 ;
  curric:id "3197"^^xsd:positiveInteger;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:29:23.920679Z"^^xsd:dateTime ;
  curric:isUnitOf
    natcurric:scheme-languages-key-stage-2 ;
  curric:includesThread
    oakcurric:thread-ask-and-answer-spoken-questions ,
    oakcurric:thread-questions ,
    oakcurric:thread-nouns-and-determiners ,
    oakcurric:thread-verb-to-have-having .

oakcurric:unit-3510
  a curric:Unit ;
  rdfs:label "Festivals and places: plural -ar/-er verbs, 'hay', 'muchos/muchas'"@en ;
  curric:slug "festivals-and-places-plural-ar-er-verbs-hay-muchos-muchas" ;
  rdfs:comment """In this unit pupils apply their knowledge of third person singular and plural -ar
  and -er verbs and new determiners ‘mucho’ and ‘todo’ to understand and communicate about
  festivals in Spain and Peru; the Tomatina, Fiestas Patrias and Inti Raymi, as well as
  aspects of Spain’s physical geography."""@en ;
  curric:whyThisWhyNow """This unit secures knowledge of third person singular and plural -ar and
  -er verbs. Having previously learnt about several cities and festivals, the unit extends
  pupils’ cultural knowledge of places where Spanish is spoken, focusing on the Tomatina
  festival in Spain, and Fiestas Patrias and Inti Raymi celebrations in Peru, as pupils now
  have the depth of linguistic knowledge to support this. New knowledge of important adjectival
  determiners ‘mucho’ and ‘todo’ is introduced and developed through the unit and will be
  revisited in further units.""" ;
  curric:hasPriorKnowledgeRequirement
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3510-1 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3510-2 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3510-3 ;
  curric:id "3510"^^xsd:positiveInteger;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:29:23.994812Z"^^xsd:dateTime ;
  curric:isUnitOf
    natcurric:scheme-languages-key-stage-2 ;
  curric:includesThread
    oakcurric:thread-the-present ,
    oakcurric:thread-cultural-spotlight .

oakcurric:unit-3501
  a curric:Unit ;
  rdfs:label "Describe things and events: 'es'"@en ;
  curric:slug "describe-things-and-events-es" ;
  rdfs:comment """In this unit, pupils learn the numbers 16-31 and the months. Using numbers, months
  and days pupils ask and answer questions about birthdays and dates of other events. They
  practise the new vocabulary through listening, reading, speaking and writing to secure the
  knowledge."""@en ;
  curric:whyThisWhyNow """Pupils will already know the numbers 1-12 and the interrogatives ‘qué’,
  ‘cómo’, ‘dónde’, ‘cuántos’ and ‘quién.’ This unit extends pupils’ knowledge of numbers to 31
  and range of questions to include ‘cuándo’ and ‘cuál’ to enable pupils to ask and answer
  questions about dates, birthday and other special events and cultural festivals. Pupils
  deepen their knowledge of vowel sounds, learning that a, o, e are strong and i, u are weak
  vowels in Spanish, and the resulting sounds when two vowels combine. In other units, pupils
  revisit numbers 1-31 as they are essential knowledge for many contexts.""" ;
  curric:hasPriorKnowledgeRequirement
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3501-1 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3501-2 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3501-3 ;
  curric:id "3501"^^xsd:positiveInteger;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:29:24.042208Z"^^xsd:dateTime ;
  curric:isUnitOf
    natcurric:scheme-languages-key-stage-2 ;
  curric:includesThread
    oakcurric:thread-verb-to-be-being .

oakcurric:unit-3507
  a curric:Unit ;
  rdfs:label "What I and others do: AR and -ER singular and plural verbs"@en ;
  curric:slug "what-i-and-others-do-ar-and-er-singular-and-plural-verbs" ;
  rdfs:comment """This unit develops pupils’ verb knowledge. Pupils use singular and new plural
  forms in various contexts, including the languages classroom, a fundraising event, daily
  activities, a dream scene and Las Fallas festival. They use negation and conjunctions
  ‘también’ and ‘pero’ in extended sentences."""@en ;
  curric:whyThisWhyNow """Pupils will already know singular forms of -er and -ar verbs, including
  ‘hacer’ to make, do. In this unit, verb knowledge is refreshed then extended to plural first
  and third persons. Statement and question patterns are secured before negation with ‘no’ with
  singular verbs is introduced, an important development in communicative range. Further
  development in language use stems from the conjunctions ‘también’ and ‘pero’ which allow
  pupils to produce compound sentences. Cultural knowledge of festivals is significantly
  developed through the comparison of Las Fallas and Guy Fawkes.""" ;
  curric:hasPriorKnowledgeRequirement
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3507-1 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3507-2 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3507-3 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3507-4 ;
  curric:id "3507"^^xsd:positiveInteger;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:29:24.074764Z"^^xsd:dateTime ;
  curric:isUnitOf
    natcurric:scheme-languages-key-stage-2 ;
  curric:includesThread
    oakcurric:thread-the-present ,
    oakcurric:thread-negation ,
    oakcurric:thread-cultural-spotlight .

oakcurric:unit-3194
  a curric:Unit ;
  rdfs:label "Me and others: 'ser' for traits"@en ;
  curric:slug "me-and-others-ser-for-traits" ;
  rdfs:comment """This unit introduces singular persons of ‘ser’, a second verb to be, being for
  permanent traits. Pupils use this verb to describe what they are like generally, and to
  say where they are from. They also learn to say what day of the week it is using ‘es’, the
  third person singular of ‘ser’."""@en ;
  curric:whyThisWhyNow """This unit builds on pupils’ knowledge of ‘estar’ to be, being for location
  and state by introducing the second verb ‘ser’ to be, being for permanent traits. Pupils
  learn to use ‘ser’ with prior knowledge of singular adjective agreement to describe their
  general personality traits. They also use ‘ser’ to say where they are from and what day of
  the week it is. At the end of the unit, pupils use ‘ser’ and ‘estar’ together to say how they
  are feeling on different days. Adjectives are revisited to embed pivotal understanding of the
  different meanings of ‘estar’ and ‘ser’.""" ;
  curric:hasPriorKnowledgeRequirement
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3194-1 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3194-2 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3194-3 ;
  curric:id "3194"^^xsd:positiveInteger;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:29:24.114009Z"^^xsd:dateTime ;
  curric:isUnitOf
    natcurric:scheme-languages-key-stage-2 ;
