    oakcurric:thread-verb-to-be-being ,
    oakcurric:thread-questions .

oakcurric:unit-3196
  a curric:Unit ;
  rdfs:label "What I and others do: singular regular verbs in the present tense"@en ;
  curric:slug "what-i-and-others-do-singular-regular-verbs-in-the-present-tense" ;
  rdfs:comment """This unit introduces infinitives and singular persons of -ar regular verbs. Pupils
  use these verbs in the context of in class and outdoor activities to ask and answer about
  what they and others do. Pupils also learn singular definite articles ‘el’ and ‘la’
  meaning ‘the’."""@en ;
  curric:whyThisWhyNow """This unit extends pupils’ knowledge of verbs, introducing them to singular
  persons of some high frequency regular -ar verbs in the present tense. Pupils build on their
  knowledge of intonation questions, extending the pattern to their growing repertoire of
  verbs, enabling them to communicate about the activities that they and other do in class and
  outdoors. Developing their knowledge of nouns and articles, pupils also learn to use singular
  definite articles ‘el’ and ‘la’ to refer to specific nouns in short sentences that also
  combine their growing knowledge of irregular and regular verbs.""" ;
  curric:hasPriorKnowledgeRequirement
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3196-1 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3196-2 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3196-3 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3196-4 ;
  curric:id "3196"^^xsd:positiveInteger;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:29:24.116620Z"^^xsd:dateTime ;
  curric:isUnitOf
    natcurric:scheme-languages-key-stage-2 ;
  curric:includesThread
    oakcurric:thread-the-present ,
    oakcurric:thread-verb-to-be-being .

oakcurric:unit-3506
  a curric:Unit ;
  rdfs:label "What I and others have: singular and plural 'tener'"@en ;
  curric:slug "what-i-and-others-have-singular-and-plural-tener" ;
  rdfs:comment """In this unit pupils use previously taught and newly learnt forms of ‘tener’ in the
  contexts of school, home and physical description. They synthesise familiar and new
  language for the purpose of describing a friend. For this they learn new carefully
  selected high frequency vocabulary."""@en ;
  curric:whyThisWhyNow """This unit first anchors pupils’ knowledge of singular forms of ‘tener’ to
  have, before introducing plural first and third persons ‘tenemos’ and ‘tienen’. New nouns,
  adjectives and adverbs are introduced, alongside familiar vocabulary, as revisiting
  previously taught phonics, vocabulary and grammar is pivotal to retaining and using them
  confidently in spoken and written communication. Soft ‘c’ sounds are revisited before
  introducing the new sound-spelling correspondence ch. Towards the end of the unit, language
  is brought together in extended production in a new context; describing a friend.""" ;
  curric:hasPriorKnowledgeRequirement
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3506-1 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3506-2 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3506-3 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3506-4 ;
  curric:id "3506"^^xsd:positiveInteger;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:29:24.121416Z"^^xsd:dateTime ;
  curric:isUnitOf
    natcurric:scheme-languages-key-stage-2 ;
  curric:includesThread
    oakcurric:thread-written-production ,
    oakcurric:thread-nouns-and-determiners ,
    oakcurric:thread-verb-to-have-having ,
    oakcurric:thread-adjectives .

oakcurric:unit-3511
  a curric:Unit ;
  rdfs:label "What we like to do: -er and -ar verbs in the 'we' form; 2-verb phrases"@en ;
  curric:slug "what-we-like-to-do-er-and-ar-verbs-in-the-we-form-2-verb-phrases" ;
  rdfs:comment """In this unit, pupils use newly introduced 2-verb structures with opinion verbs
  ‘amar’ and ‘odiar’ to say what they like and hate doing, and modal verbs ‘deber’ and
  ‘querer’ to say what they must do and want to do. Contexts include household chores, rules
  at school, Lanzarote in summer and a poem."""@en ;
  curric:whyThisWhyNow """Pupils will already know first person plural -ar and -er verbs and opinion
  verbs ‘amar’ and ‘odiar’. This unit secures this knowledge first, before introducing 2-verb
  structures with opinion verbs, then modal verbs ‘deber’ and ‘querer’. This is the final new
  structure pupils learn in the course, so knowledge is developed over several lessons in the
  unit. In the latter part of this unit pupils extend their knowledge by responding creatively
  in speaking and writing to an authentic poem with a 2-verb structure as its linguistic
  anchor, ‘Quiero ver una vaca’ by Enrique Fierro.""" ;
  curric:hasPriorKnowledgeRequirement
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3511-1 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3511-2 ;
  curric:id "3511"^^xsd:positiveInteger;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:29:24.249311Z"^^xsd:dateTime ;
  curric:isUnitOf
    natcurric:scheme-languages-key-stage-2 ;
  curric:includesThread
    oakcurric:thread-written-production ,
    oakcurric:thread-the-present ,
    oakcurric:thread-cultural-spotlight ,
    oakcurric:thread-nouns-and-determiners ,
    oakcurric:thread-adjectives .

oakcurric:unit-3504
  a curric:Unit ;
  rdfs:label "Me and others: plural 'estar' (for states) and 'ser' (for traits)"@en ;
  curric:slug "me-and-others-plural-estar-for-states-and-ser-for-traits" ;
  rdfs:comment """This unit requires pupils to use ‘estar’ and ‘ser’ effectively to communicate
  about how others are today and what they are like in general. When using the new plural
  forms ‘están’ and ‘son’ in the context of the festival ‘El Día de los Muertos’, pupils
  also use plural forms of familiar adjectives."""@en ;
  curric:whyThisWhyNow """This unit builds pupils’ knowledge of the high frequency verbs ‘estar’ and
  ‘ser’, adding the third person plural forms ‘están’ and ‘son’. Pupils practise the new plural
  forms ‘they are’ together with complementary regular plural adjective agreement. Consistent
  with other units, ‘estar’ for states is contrasted with ‘ser’ for traits. In the second part
  of this unit, new and revisited language is synthesised in the new cultural context of ‘El
  Día de los Muertos’, a festival widely celebrated in Latin America. Knowledge of strong and
  weak vowel combinations is secured.""" ;
  curric:hasPriorKnowledgeRequirement
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3504-1 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3504-2 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3504-3 ;
  curric:id "3504"^^xsd:positiveInteger;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:29:24.339613Z"^^xsd:dateTime ;
  curric:isUnitOf
    natcurric:scheme-languages-key-stage-2 ;
  curric:includesThread
    oakcurric:thread-cultural-spotlight ,
    oakcurric:thread-adjectives ,
    oakcurric:thread-verb-to-be-being .

oakcurric:unit-3198
  a curric:Unit ;
  rdfs:label "In class: infinitive verbs, estar + location/state"@en ;
  curric:slug "in-class-infinitive-verbs-estar-plus-location-state" ;
  rdfs:comment """In this unit, pupils embed vowel sounds and singular persons of 'estar' to be,
  being. They respond to the register and ask and answer questions about how and where they
  are. Pupils learn new verbs in the context of classroom instructions and practise
  listening and responding to these."""@en ;
  curric:whyThisWhyNow """This unit strengthens essential knowledge of the vowel sounds and secures
  knowledge of ‘estar’ to be, being, one of the most frequent Spanish verbs. Secure use of
  ‘estar’ in short statements and both intonation and information questions enables pupils to
  initiate short interactions. Having previously learnt a number of -ar verbs, pupils now
  increase their verb repertoire in the classroom context, developing their aural understanding
  of teacher instructions. In later units, pupils will continue to extend the number of verbs
  they can use in the present tense.""" ;
  curric:hasPriorKnowledgeRequirement
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3198-1 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3198-2 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3198-3 ;
  curric:id "3198"^^xsd:positiveInteger;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:29:24.414197Z"^^xsd:dateTime ;
  curric:isUnitOf
    natcurric:scheme-languages-key-stage-2 ;
  curric:includesThread
    oakcurric:thread-the-present ,
    oakcurric:thread-verb-to-be-being .

oakcurric:unit-3201
  a curric:Unit ;
  rdfs:label "What I and others do: singular regular verbs in the present"@en ;
  curric:slug "what-i-and-others-do-singular-regular-verbs-in-the-present" ;
  rdfs:comment """In this unit, pupils use singular forms of -ar and -er verbs, including the
  irregular verb ‘hacer’ to make, do in order to ask and answer questions in the present
  tense. New high frequency vocabulary gives pupils more words to talk about activities.
  Hard sounds ga, go, gu, ca, co, cu are revisited."""@en ;
  curric:whyThisWhyNow """This unit builds on pupils’ previous knowledge of -ar verbs by growing
  their verb lexicon and introducing singular persons of -er verbs and the highly frequent
  irregular verb ‘hacer’ to do, make. Revisiting key verb patterns with new verbs is essential
  to securing the knowledge. Similarly, providing multiple opportunities to practise asking and
  answering questions with new vocabulary develops pupils’ communicative competence. In later
  units pupils will extend their knowledge from singular to plural forms of these verbs in the
  present tense.""" ;
  curric:hasPriorKnowledgeRequirement
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3201-1 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3201-2 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3201-3 ;
  curric:id "3201"^^xsd:positiveInteger;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:29:24.466813Z"^^xsd:dateTime ;
  curric:isUnitOf
    natcurric:scheme-languages-key-stage-2 ;
  curric:includesThread
    oakcurric:thread-ask-and-answer-spoken-questions ,
    oakcurric:thread-the-present ,
    oakcurric:thread-questions .

oakcurric:unit-3193
  a curric:Unit ;
  rdfs:label "Me and others: 'estar' for location and state"@en ;
  curric:slug "me-and-others-estar-for-location-and-state" ;
  rdfs:comment """In this unit, in the context of the classroom, pupils learn first, second and
  third person singular forms of the verb 'estar' and singular regular adjective agreement.
  They use statements, intonation and information questions with ' ¿cómo?' and '¿dónde?' to
  communicate how and where people are."""@en ;
  curric:whyThisWhyNow """This unit introduces the verb ‘estar’ to be, being for location and state,
  which is essential early knowledge for pupils. Singular regular adjective agreement for
  gender is key knowledge for communicating temporary states and moods effectively. High
  frequency vocabulary is selected to support this communicative purpose. Pupils also learn
  greetings to enable them to initiate first interactions in Spanish. In another unit, pupils
  extend their knowledge of adjective agreement and apply it to grammatically gendered nouns.""" ;
  curric:hasPriorKnowledgeRequirement
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3193-1 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3193-2 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3193-3 ;
  curric:id "3193"^^xsd:positiveInteger;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:29:24.552937Z"^^xsd:dateTime ;
  curric:isUnitOf
    natcurric:scheme-languages-key-stage-2 ;
  curric:includesThread
    oakcurric:thread-ask-and-answer-spoken-questions ,
    oakcurric:thread-adjectives ,
    oakcurric:thread-verb-to-be-being ,
    oakcurric:thread-questions .

oakcurric:unit-3202
  a curric:Unit ;
  rdfs:label "Likes and dislikes: singular opinion verbs"@en ;
  curric:slug "likes-and-dislikes-singular-opinion-verbs" ;
  rdfs:comment """In this unit, pupils use singular persons of new verbs ‘amar’ to love and ‘odiar’
  to hate to express opinions. They use reference resources to personalise their responses,
  researching new nouns. Pupils also develop their phonics knowledge, practising two new
  sounds, r and rr."""@en ;
  curric:whyThisWhyNow """Pupils will already know a range of -ar verbs in the present tense. This
  unit introduces two new -ar verbs, ‘amar’ to love and ‘odiar’ to hate, which enable pupils to
  ask for and give opinions, extending their communicative repertoire. Already familiar with
  definite articles ‘el’ and ‘la’, pupils are well placed to learn the plural definite articles
  ‘los’ and ‘las’, and that they need to use definite articles after opinion verbs, where they
  are not used in English. Trickier sound-symbol correspondences r, rr are introduced now that
  pupils are confident with easier sounds.""" ;
  curric:hasPriorKnowledgeRequirement
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3202-1 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3202-2 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3202-3 ;
  curric:id "3202"^^xsd:positiveInteger;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:29:24.655635Z"^^xsd:dateTime ;
  curric:isUnitOf
    natcurric:scheme-languages-key-stage-2 ;
  curric:includesThread
    oakcurric:thread-the-present ,
    oakcurric:thread-use-reference-resources .

oakcurric:unit-3505
  a curric:Unit ;
  rdfs:label "Christmas traditions in the Spanish-speaking world"@en ;
  curric:slug "christmas-traditions-in-the-spanish-speaking-world" ;
  rdfs:comment """In this unit, pupils revisit numbers and learn more about Christmas traditions in
  Spain, specifically ‘El Gordo’, the national Christmas lottery. They practise the full
  range of known sound-spelling links by listening and joining in with a traditional
  Christmas song in Spanish."""@en ;
  curric:whyThisWhyNow """Pupils will already know some information about Christmas in Spain and
  Peru. This unit deepens their knowledge of this important cultural event widely celebrated in
  the Hispanic world. Pupils learn about the Spanish tradition of ‘El Gordo’, the Christmas
  lottery, and revisit numbers. They also listen to and join in with a traditional Christmas
  song in Spanish, adding to the range of texts they respond to and further strengthening
  knowledge of all previously taught sound-symbol correspondences.""" ;
  curric:hasPriorKnowledgeRequirement
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3505-1 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3505-2 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3505-3 ;
  curric:id "3505"^^xsd:positiveInteger;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:29:25.781120Z"^^xsd:dateTime ;
  curric:isUnitOf
    natcurric:scheme-languages-key-stage-2 ;
  curric:includesThread
    oakcurric:thread-cultural-spotlight .

oakcurric:unit-3199
  a curric:Unit ;
  rdfs:label "Ask how many: 'tener', 'hay', numbers, information questions with 'cuántos/as'"@en ;
  curric:slug "ask-how-many-tener-hay-numbers-information-questions-with-cuantos-as" ;
  rdfs:comment """In this unit pupils anchor numbers 1-12 and key sounds que, qui, ce, ci. They add
  -s or -es to form plural nouns, learning determiners ‘unos’ and ‘unas’ and interrogatives
  ‘cuántos’ and ‘cuántas’, which they use to ask and answer about how many in the context of
  a carnival."""@en ;
  curric:whyThisWhyNow """Pupils will already know how to use plural nouns with numbers 1-12. In
  this unit, pupils extend their repertoire of determiners to ‘unos’ and ‘unas’ and
  interrogatives ‘cuántos’ and ‘cuántas’. This unit strengthens knowledge of que, qui, ce, ci
  to discern these hard and soft sounds securely and develops cultural knowledge through the
  context of carnival. Combining prior knowledge of ‘tener’ and ‘hay’ with new determiners and
  interrogatives, pupils ask and answer questions with numbers and new, high frequency nouns.
  Pupils will extend their repertoire of numbers and nouns in later units.""" ;
  curric:hasPriorKnowledgeRequirement
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3199-1 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3199-2 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3199-3 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3199-4 ;
  curric:id "3199"^^xsd:positiveInteger;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:29:25.821446Z"^^xsd:dateTime ;
  curric:isUnitOf
    natcurric:scheme-languages-key-stage-2 ;
  curric:includesThread
    oakcurric:thread-ask-and-answer-spoken-questions ,
    oakcurric:thread-the-present ,
    oakcurric:thread-questions ,
    oakcurric:thread-nouns-and-determiners ,
    oakcurric:thread-verb-to-have-having .

